---
title: SaaS Analytics Dashboard
projectContext: A B2B SaaS startup had built a powerful data analytics product but was losing customers during onboarding because the dashboard was too complex to navigate. Churn in the first 30 days was running at 34%, and user interviews consistently pointed to the same issue — customers couldn't find the insights they were paying for.
problem: The dashboard had grown organically over three years of feature development without a coherent information architecture. Power users loved it, but new customers were overwhelmed. The navigation had 47 top-level items, charts lacked context, and there was no guided path to the "aha moment" that made the product valuable. The engineering team had been adding features faster than the UX could absorb them.
solution: Conducted a full UX audit and information architecture redesign, reducing the primary navigation to 8 items organized around user goals rather than product features. Built a new onboarding flow with progressive disclosure, contextual tooltips, and a "quick wins" dashboard that surfaced the three most actionable insights for each customer's data profile.
outcome: 30-day churn dropped from 34% to 11% within two quarters of the redesign launch. Time-to-first-insight (the key activation metric) fell from an average of 4.2 days to 18 hours. Net Promoter Score increased by 22 points, and the sales team reported that demo-to-close rates improved because prospects could understand the product value in a single session.
